---
// Experiments.astro - Experiments section organized by Questions (accordion)

const basePath = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---
<section id="experiments" class="content-section">
  <div class="section-container">
    <h2 class="section-title">Experiments</h2>
    <p class="section-subtitle">Click each question to expand the evidence.</p>

    <!-- Part I -->
    <p class="q-group-eyebrow">Part I</p>
    <h3 class="q-group-title">Main Results &amp; Design Choices</h3>

    <!-- Q1 -->
    <div class="q-block" id="q1">
      <button class="q-header" aria-expanded="false" data-target="q1-body">
        <span class="q-badge">Q 1</span>
        <h3>Does Chameleon jointly handle compositing and stylization while preserving identity?</h3>
        <span class="q-summary">Yes. Consistently outperforms baselines across qualitative results and identity / stylization / compositional metrics.</span>
        <span class="q-chevron" aria-hidden="true">
          <svg width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><polyline points="6 8 10 12 14 8"/></svg>
        </span>
      </button>
      <div class="q-body" id="q1-body">
        <p class="q-lead"><strong>Yes.</strong> Chameleon consistently outperforms two-stage and commercial baselines across qualitative results (Figure 7) and <strong>identity</strong> (CLIP-I), <strong>stylization</strong> (CSD), and <strong>compositional</strong> VLM metrics (Table 2).</p>

        <img src={`${basePath}assets/experiments/1.png`} alt="Qualitative comparison — Figure 7" class="q-fig" />
        <p class="q-caption"><strong>Figure 7.</strong> Cross-domain compositing results by our Chameleon. <strong>(a)</strong> preserves foreground <strong>identity</strong>, <strong>(b)</strong> maintains consistent <strong>style</strong>, and <strong>(c)</strong> aligned <strong>geometry</strong> and <strong>(d)</strong> grounded <strong>shadows</strong> demonstrate compositional plausibility. <strong>(e)</strong> Chameleon outperforms <strong>two-stage</strong> cascaded pipelines that combine style transfer and object insertion (<i style="color:#c0392b;">over-stylizing</i> the foreground), as well as <strong>commercial models</strong> (GPT-Image 2, Nano-Banana 2) that shift background tone or ignore the input mask.</p>

        <img src={`${basePath}assets/experiments/2.png`} alt="Quantitative comparison — Table 2" class="q-fig" />
        <p class="q-caption"><strong>Table 2.</strong> Quantitative comparison on TF-ICON and AIComposer benchmarks. Our Chameleon achieves <strong>best</strong> results across metrics measuring <strong>identity</strong>, <strong>stylization</strong>, and <strong>compositionality</strong>. CSD is the only <strong>second-best</strong> result, since high CSD on the <strong>2-stage</strong> cascaded pipeline reflects <i style="color:#c0392b;">over-stylization</i> (Figure 7(e)).</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Q2 -->
    <div class="q-block" id="q2">
      <button class="q-header" aria-expanded="false" data-target="q2-body">
        <span class="q-badge">Q 2</span>
        <h3>Why DINOv3 with this layer selection?</h3>
        <span class="q-summary">DINOv3 yields the strongest disentanglement among off-the-shelf encoders, with mid layers (12-14) for style and late layers (18-20) for content.</span>
        <span class="q-chevron" aria-hidden="true">
          <svg width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><polyline points="6 8 10 12 14 8"/></svg>
        </span>
      </button>
      <div class="q-body" id="q2-body">
        <p class="q-lead"><strong>DINOv3</strong> achieves the strongest overall disentanglement margin Δ among frozen off-the-shelf encoders (Table 3), making it the most suitable foundation for training built upon our proposed <strong>JHCL</strong> loss. Within DINOv3, <strong>mid layers (12-14)</strong> yield the smallest negative margin on the style-paired split while <strong>late layers (18-20)</strong> provide substantially stronger content separation (Table 4), motivating why DINOv3 and these layers (12-14 for the style head, 18-20 for the content head) are selected.</p>
        <img src={`${basePath}assets/experiments/3.png`} alt="Backbone comparison — Table 3" class="q-fig" />
        <p class="q-caption"><strong>Table 3.</strong> Why DINOv3? <strong>Disentanglement margin Δ</strong> on the dual-anchor test across frozen <strong>off-the-shelf encoders</strong> (without any projection head). DINOv3 achieves the <strong>strongest</strong> overall margin, especially on the content-paired split.</p>
        <img src={`${basePath}assets/experiments/4.png`} alt="Layer selection for style and content heads — Table 4" class="q-fig" />
        <p class="q-caption"><strong>Table 4.</strong> Layer selection for the style and content heads. Within DINOv3, <strong>mid layers (12-14)</strong> yield the smallest negative margin on the style-paired split, while <strong>late layers (18-20)</strong> provide substantially stronger content separation.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Part II -->
    <p class="q-group-eyebrow part-two">Part II</p>
    <h3 class="q-group-title">Analysis</h3>

    <!-- Q3 -->
    <div class="q-block" id="q3">
      <button class="q-header" aria-expanded="false" data-target="q3-body">
        <span class="q-badge">Q 3</span>
        <h3>Does STAG work effectively without collapse?</h3>
        <span class="q-summary">Yes. STAG adaptively gates style injection both spatially (foreground-focused) and temporally (amplifying at later denoising steps, adaptive rather than fixed-schedule), without per-block collapse.</span>
        <span class="q-chevron" aria-hidden="true">
          <svg width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><polyline points="6 8 10 12 14 8"/></svg>
        </span>
      </button>
      <div class="q-body" id="q3-body">
        <p class="q-lead"><strong>Yes.</strong> <strong>STAG</strong> <strong>adaptively</strong> gates style injection across both <strong>spatial</strong> and <strong>temporal</strong> axes. <strong>(a)</strong> <em>Spatially</em>, attention concentrates on the foreground region. <strong>(c)</strong> <em>Temporally</em>, stronger stylization emerges at later denoising steps, aligning with prior research, but unlike prior <strong>fixed schedules</strong>, we condition <strong>adaptively</strong> on the denoising stage via <strong>learnable gating</strong>. <strong>(d)</strong> Per-block gating <strong>dynamically activates and suppresses</strong> style injection without collapsing.</p>
        <img src={`${basePath}assets/experiments/5.png`} alt="Effect of STAG — Figure 8" class="q-fig" />
        <p class="q-caption"><strong>Figure 8.</strong> Effect of <strong>Spatio-Temporal Attention Gating (STAG)</strong>. Attention from the foreground query (white box) to <em>S<sub>T</sub>(I<sub>bg</sub>)</em>. <strong>(a, b)</strong> STAG-on / STAG-off attention maps. <strong>(c)</strong> Per-step attention to <em>S<sub>T</sub>(I<sub>bg</sub>)</em> across denoising steps. <strong>(d)</strong> Per-block amplification ratio (STAG-on / STAG-off).</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Q4 -->
    <div class="q-block" id="q4">
      <button class="q-header" aria-expanded="false" data-target="q4-body">
        <span class="q-badge">Q 4</span>
        <h3>Is ChameleonDataset<sub>ev</sub> a better benchmark than existing ones?</h3>
        <span class="q-summary">Yes. ChameleonDataset_ev evaluates challenging cross-domain cases beyond the redundant foreground × background combinations and simple scenarios in prior benchmarks.</span>
        <span class="q-chevron" aria-hidden="true">
          <svg width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><polyline points="6 8 10 12 14 8"/></svg>
        </span>
      </button>
      <div class="q-body" id="q4-body">
        <p class="q-lead"><strong>Yes.</strong> Prior benchmarks such as <strong>TF-ICON</strong> inflate sample count via foreground × background combinations (10 × 10 = 100 <i style="color:#c0392b;">redundant</i> pairs) and remain limited to <i style="color:#c0392b;">simple compositional scenarios</i>. In contrast, <strong>ChameleonDataset<sub>ev</sub></strong> evaluates <strong>challenging cross-domain cases</strong>, including <strong>(a)</strong> foreground-background interaction, <strong>(b)</strong> lighting-grounded shadows, <strong>(c)</strong> reflective surfaces, and <strong>(d-g)</strong> diverse unique background styles.</p>
        <img src={`${basePath}assets/experiments/6.png`} alt="Representative cases in ChameleonDataset_ev — Figure 9" class="q-fig" />
        <p class="q-caption"><strong>Figure 9.</strong> Representative cases in <strong>ChameleonDataset<sub>ev</sub></strong>. <strong>(a)</strong> Natural foreground interaction (climbing stairs). <strong>(b)</strong> Lighting-consistent shadow grounding. <strong>(c)</strong> Reflection on reflective surfaces. <strong>(d-g)</strong> Diverse background styles (motion blur, mosaic, pixel-art, grayscale).</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Q5 -->
    <div class="q-block" id="q5">
      <button class="q-header" aria-expanded="false" data-target="q5-body">
        <span class="q-badge">Q 5</span>
        <h3>Is Chameleon's computational cost manageable?</h3>
        <span class="q-summary">Yes. Only +0.21% trainable parameters relative to the frozen DiT backbone and inference latency overhead &lt; 1s, while JHCL and STAG together deliver substantial gains on identity, stylization, and aesthetic metrics.</span>
        <span class="q-chevron" aria-hidden="true">
          <svg width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><polyline points="6 8 10 12 14 8"/></svg>
        </span>
      </button>
      <div class="q-body" id="q5-body">
        <p class="q-lead"><strong>Yes.</strong> Only <strong>+0.21%</strong> trainable parameters relative to the frozen DiT backbone (Table 5), and adding 392 DINO tokens (196 style + 196 content) incurs <strong>&lt; 1s</strong> latency overhead (<strong>+0.22s</strong> on res 512, <strong>+0.55s</strong> on res 1024, 28-step) (Table 6), while heads trained from the <strong>JHCL</strong> loss output tokens that improve both <strong>identity</strong> (CLIP-I) and <strong>stylization</strong> (CSD), and <strong>STAG</strong> further boosts <strong>stylization</strong> metrics (CSD, AES) (Table 7).</p>

        <div class="q-table-grid">
          <div>
            <img src={`${basePath}assets/experiments/7.png`} alt="Trainable parameter budget — Table 5" class="q-fig" />
            <p class="q-caption"><strong>Table 5.</strong> Trainable parameter budget. <strong>STAG</strong> adds only 0.1M params (&lt;0.01% of the backbone).</p>
          </div>
          <div>
            <img src={`${basePath}assets/experiments/8.png`} alt="Inference overhead — Table 6" class="q-fig" />
            <p class="q-caption"><strong>Table 6.</strong> Inference overhead from <strong>+392 DINO tokens</strong> (196 style + 196 content). Adds <strong>+0.22s</strong> on res 512 (0.98s → 1.20s) and <strong>+0.55s</strong> on res 1024 (2.58s → 3.13s) for 28-step inference.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <img src={`${basePath}assets/experiments/9.png`} alt="Component ablation — Table 7" class="q-fig" />
        <p class="q-caption"><strong>Table 7.</strong> Component ablation. <strong>JHCL</strong> improves both <strong>identity</strong> (CLIP-I) and <strong>stylization</strong> (CSD); <strong>STAG</strong> further improves <strong>stylization</strong> metrics (CSD, AES).</p>
      </div>
    </div>

  </div>
</section>

<script is:inline>
  (function() {
    function initQAccordion() {
      var headers = document.querySelectorAll('#experiments .q-header[data-target]');
      headers.forEach(function(header) {
        header.setAttribute('type', 'button');
        header.addEventListener('click', function(e) {
          e.preventDefault();
          var targetId = header.getAttribute('data-target');
          if (!targetId) return;
          var body = document.getElementById(targetId);
          if (!body) return;

          var isOpen = header.getAttribute('aria-expanded') === 'true';

          headers.forEach(function(h) {
            var tid = h.getAttribute('data-target');
            if (tid && tid !== targetId) {
              h.setAttribute('aria-expanded', 'false');
              var b = document.getElementById(tid);
              if (b) b.style.maxHeight = '0px';
            }
          });

          if (isOpen) {
            header.setAttribute('aria-expanded', 'false');
            body.style.maxHeight = '0px';
          } else {
            header.setAttribute('aria-expanded', 'true');
            body.style.maxHeight = body.scrollHeight + 'px';
            var imgs = body.querySelectorAll('img');
            imgs.forEach(function(img) {
              if (!img.complete) {
                img.addEventListener('load', function() {
                  if (header.getAttribute('aria-expanded') === 'true') {
                    body.style.maxHeight = body.scrollHeight + 'px';
                  }
                }, { once: true });
              }
            });
          }
        });
      });
    }

    if (document.readyState === 'loading') {
      document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', initQAccordion);
    } else {
      initQAccordion();
    }
  })();
</script>

<style>
  .section-subtitle {
    text-align: center;
    color: #888;
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    margin-bottom: 2rem;
    margin-top: -0.5rem;
  }

  .q-group-eyebrow {
    text-align: center;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.18em;
    font-size: 0.8rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    color: #2D8F47;
    margin: 0 0 0.5rem;
  }

  .q-group-eyebrow.part-two {
    margin-top: 3rem;
  }

  .q-group-title {
    text-align: center;
    font-size: 1.6rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    color: #1F5E36;
    margin: 0 auto 1.5rem;
    max-width: 820px;
    line-height: 1.3;
    font-family: 'Georgia', 'Times New Roman', serif;
    font-style: italic;
  }

  .q-fig {
    width: 100%;
    height: auto;
    border-radius: 8px;
    display: block;
    margin-bottom: 0.6rem;
  }

  .q-caption {
    font-size: 0.88rem;
    color: #666;
    line-height: 1.55;
    margin: 0 0 1.5rem 0;
    padding: 0 0.5rem;
    border-left: 3px solid #e0e0e0;
  }

  .q-caption strong { color: #1F5E36; }

  .q-lead {
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    color: #444;
    line-height: 1.7;
    margin-bottom: 1.2rem;
  }

  .q-lead strong { color: #1F5E36; }

  .q-table-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;
    gap: 1.5rem;
    margin-bottom: 1.2rem;
  }
  .q-table-grid img { margin-bottom: 0.6rem; }
  .q-table-grid .q-caption { margin-bottom: 0; }

  @media (max-width: 700px) {
    .q-table-grid { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
  }

  .q-block {
    background: white;
    border-radius: 14px;
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
    box-shadow: 0 4px 20px rgba(0,0,0,0.07);
    scroll-margin-top: 80px;
    overflow: hidden;
  }

  .q-header {
    display: flex;
    align-items: flex-start;
    gap: 1rem;
    padding: 1.5rem 2rem;
    width: 100%;
    background: none;
    border: none;
    cursor: pointer;
    text-align: left;
    font-family: inherit;
    color: inherit;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    transition: background-color 0.15s ease;
  }

  .q-header:hover {
    background-color: #f6faf3;
  }

  .q-badge {
    background: #1F5E36;
    color: white;
    font-size: 0.8rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    padding: 4px 12px;
    border-radius: 20px;
    white-space: nowrap;
    letter-spacing: 0.05em;
    flex-shrink: 0;
    margin-top: 2px;
  }

  .q-header h3 {
    margin: 0;
    font-size: 1.2rem;
    color: #0E3A1F;
    font-weight: 700;
    line-height: 1.35;
    flex: 1;
    min-width: 200px;
  }

  .q-summary {
    display: block;
    width: 100%;
    padding-left: calc(12px + 1rem + 32px);
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    color: #666;
    line-height: 1.5;
    margin-top: 0.3rem;
    font-weight: 500;
    font-style: italic;
  }

  .q-chevron {
    flex-shrink: 0;
    color: #999;
    transition: transform 0.3s ease;
    margin-top: 4px;
  }

  .q-header[aria-expanded="true"] .q-chevron {
    transform: rotate(180deg);
  }

  .q-header[aria-expanded="true"] .q-summary {
    display: none;
  }

  .q-body {
    max-height: 0;
    overflow: hidden;
    transition: max-height 0.4s ease;
    padding: 0 2rem;
  }

  .q-header[aria-expanded="true"] + .q-body {
    padding: 0 2rem 2rem;
  }

  @media (max-width: 768px) {
    .q-header { padding: 1.2rem 1.5rem; }
    .q-body { padding: 0 1.5rem; }
    .q-header[aria-expanded="true"] + .q-body { padding: 0 1.5rem 1.5rem; }
    .q-header h3 { font-size: 1.05rem; }
    .q-summary { padding-left: 0; }
  }
</style>
